  [2] It is publicly traded but not listed on an exchange, which does limit=
 its trading.


  [3] Another important existing box of Bitcoins is   MicroStrategy Inc., w=
hich is even more freely tradeable than GBTC but tracks Bitcoin even less c=
losely.


  [4] You can caveat this. People sometimes worry that proof-of-stake Ether=
eum, in which staking is dominated by a few large intermediaries, creates v=
ulnerability to censorship: If Coinbase Global Inc. runs a big staking serv=
ice, and the SEC tells it not to recognize certain transactions by actors t=
he SEC dislikes, will Coinbase have to go along? Of course in the real worl=
d the SEC just thinks Coinbase=E2=80=99s whole staking service is illegal a=
nd  wants to shut it down, so Coinbase doesn=E2=80=99t have much incentive =
to help out the SEC.


  [5] I=E2=80=99m implicitly assuming that the home's price hasn=E2=80=99t =
changed, my mortgage is pretty fresh, and the mortgage principal amounts wo=
uld be about the same. Those assumptions are not super-realistic, but I=E2=
=80=99m not sure they=E2=80=99re always that far off either.


  [6] Only arguably worse, though; it sort of depends on the counterfactual=
. If the counterfactual is =E2=80=9Cyou don=E2=80=99t buy my house, I stay =
there for 30 years paying 3%, and you keep renting,=E2=80=9D the banks migh=
t prefer some activity even if it crystallizes some losses.


  [7] I have no idea what the mechanics are here =E2=80=94 like, how do the=
y make sure that the vote sellers actually vote the way they are supposed t=
o? =E2=80=94 though I suspect it=E2=80=99s not too hard. They say they work=
 with a bunch of brokers=E2=80=99 systems.


