<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Portable credit</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked a while back about <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33892453.286409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTMveWllbGRzdHJlZXQtbWlzc2=
VkLWEtYm9hdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91926789" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  assumable mortgages</a>.=
=C2=A0A lot of homeowners in the US have mortgages with 3%-ish interest rat=
es that they got a few years ago, but if you try to get a mortgage today, i=
t will have a 7%-ish interest rate. If I own a house and have a 3% mortgage=
, and I want to sell it to you and you want to buy it, you will go to a ban=
k and get a 7% mortgage, and your bank will give you the money, and you wil=
l give me the money, and I will give the money to my bank to pay off my 3% =
mortgage. This seems very inefficient. You are borrowing expensive money to=
 give to me to pay off a cheap mortgage early.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be better for me, and for you, if you=
 could just=C2=A0<em>assume=C2=A0</em>my mortgage =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you cou=
ld move into my house and keep making the 3% payments on my mortgage, inste=
ad of making the new 7% payments.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(It would arguably be worse=C2=A0<em>for our banks:=C2=A0</em>My =
bank would rather get its below-market 3% mortgage paid off early at par, a=
nd your bank would rather originate a new market-rate mortgage.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the US, some mortgages are, with some conto=
rtions and hoop-jumping, assumable: Their terms provide that, if we recite =
exactly the right incantations, you can take over my mortgage and keep payi=
ng 3%. But most aren=E2=80=99t. And a problem in the US housing market now =
is that everyone who has a 3% mortgage can=E2=80=99t move, because they=E2=
=80=99d need to get a 7% mortgage somewhere else, which constrains supply.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Private equity buyouts also work that way? Lik=
e the way a private equity buyout works is that a fund borrows a lot of mon=
ey from lenders to pay some of the purchase price for the company, and then=
 it pays down those loans over time. And if it sells the company to another=
 private equity firm while the loans are still outstanding, then ordinarily=
 the loans come due immediately, so the new private equity buyer has to go =
to=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>lenders to get new loans to pay the old private e=
quity owner the money to hand over to=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>lenders. And j=
ust as with mortgages, if the old owner got its loans during a period of lo=
w rates and easy credit, and the new buyer has to get its loans during a pe=
riod of high rates and more difficult credit, some trades won=E2=80=99t get=
 done: The company is worth more to the old owner, with its cheap debt, tha=
n it will be to a new owner with expensive debt.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The analogy is not perfect: A lot of the priva=
te-equity loans will be floating-rate, so the difference is not so much =E2=
=80=9C3% rates versus 7% rates=E2=80=9D as it is =E2=80=9Crelatively easy c=
redit versus more nervous credit.=E2=80=9D And =E2=80=9Cthe loans come due =
immediately=E2=80=9D can mean less =E2=80=9Cthe loans come due immediately=
=E2=80=9D and more =E2=80=9Cthe loans=C2=A0<em>technically=C2=A0</em>come d=
ue immediately, which gives the lenders negotiating leverage to extract fee=
s and concessions for agreeing to roll them over for the new buyer.=E2=80=
=9D But the basic idea is that if private-equity buyout loans were assumabl=
e, then more deals would get done, because buyers wouldn=E2=80=99t have to =
worry about going out and getting new loans in tougher credit environments.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0John Sage an=
d Ellen Schneider on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/33892453.286409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjQtMDEtMDQvcHJpdmF0ZS1jcmVkaXQtaGVscHMtcGUtcGVlcnMtYnktbWFraW5nLWRlYWwtZml=
